    "long_instructions": "### **What is a DDoS Attack?**\r\n\r\nA **Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS)** attack happens when many devices flood a website or server with requests at the same time. This overwhelms the system, slows it down, or crashes it, preventing others from getting in.\r\n\r\nNot all DDoS events are intentional. Sometimes, huge demand - like everyone trying to get Taylor Swift tickets - can break the system too.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n#### **Scenario: The Great Ticket Rush**\r\n\r\nIt's the day of the big presale. You're one of thousands trying to score tickets online. As fans flood the site, it struggles to keep up.\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 1: Click \"Get Tickets\"**\r\n\r\nYour browser is already open to the event. Click the button to start the process of joining the queue.\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 2: Join the Queue**\r\n\r\nClick \"Join the Queue.\" You'll enter the waiting room as the system tries to manage overwhelming traffic.\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 3: Wait Patiently**\r\n\r\nWatch what happens next. Over the next 20 seconds, the system attempts to place you in line. More and more users are entering...\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 4: Enter the Queue**\r\n\r\nYou're finally in, but there are **tens of thousands** of people ahead of you. The site starts to slow.\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 5: System Overload**\r\n\r\nAs pressure builds, the site errors out. Eventually, it crashes entirely. Even though you didn't attack the site, your traffic, combined with everyone else's, overwhelmed it.\r\n\r\n<br/><br/><br/>",
